@ancelkeyslegacy @MichelSpeiser Yes, deductive logic in the sense of having semantics, syntactics, rules of inference etc.
except it is not classical logic (which does not capture causation). See its axiomatic characterization here:  https://t.co/ZSUcowuZ4z
Section 7.3, page 228.

@MichelSpeiser Good question. "Inevitable" is  equivalent to "logically necessary" and cannot be shown to hold unless we have a logic to go by. CI
provides a logic for cause-effect relationships,
which traditional statistics  lacks. The mantra "correlation is not causation" is a theorem in CI.

@pbleic @ChristosArgyrop @f2harrell @stephensenn @AndrewPGrieve @PavlosMsaouel @soboleffspaces @smueller I would love to hear what other problems in RCT context you would have liked an intervention-calculus to solve for you. Chances are, it is someplace in the CI literature, like this one:
https://t.co/BPAzNCpMxe
If not, we probably  tell you if a solution exists.
